<h2>Lifecycle</h2>
<p>The reference runtime for the <a href="/projects/weblifecycle/">Web Lifecycle</a> protocol — a domain
entity's declared status set and the guarded, role-scoped transitions between them. A loan, a policy, a
claim, an order, a ticket: each is a state machine
(<code>draft → submitted → … → closed</code>) whose legal moves depend on the actor and on guard
predicates. The block ships the protocol's seam and nothing about the engine behind it.</p>

<h3>What it provides</h3>
<ul>
  <li><code>LifecycleDefinition</code> — the data-defined status set + transition map (each edge:
    <code>from → to</code>, an optional <code>guard</code>, the permitted <code>actor</code>). The map is
    the only lock — portable across engines.</li>
  <li><code>CustomLifecycleProvider</code> — the swappable contract: <code>available(entity, actor)</code>
    and <code>transition(entity, to, actor)</code>.</li>
  <li><code>DefaultLifecycleProvider</code> — a native-first, in-memory reference satisfying the contract
    (deterministic under test via an injectable clock); a workflow engine plugs in behind the same
    interface.</li>
  <li><code>CustomLifecycleRegistry</code> (<code>window.customLifecycles</code>) — named providers the
    project selects or overrides via the injector chain.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What it deliberately does not own</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Authorization</strong> — <em>whether</em> an actor may fire an edge is a guard predicate,
    delegated to a <code>GuardResolver</code> (the <a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a> seam).
    The default resolver is permissive (there is no native authorization primitive); a real authz
    provider is async and server-authoritative.</li>
  <li><strong>Persistence</strong> — where the entity (and its current status) is stored is the entity's
    own concern.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Composition</h3>
<p>Every applied transition emits a <code>LifecycleEvent</code> (<code>{ entity, from, to, actor, at }</code>)
— the composition seam for audit-trail (<a href="/backlog/357-audit-trail-standard/">#357</a>) and
reporting. The canonical display of the current state + available next moves is the
<a href="/intents/status-indicator/">Status Indicator</a> intent. The first real consumer is the
<a href="/backlog/317-exercise-app-loan-origination/">loan-origination exercise app</a>.</p>
